               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350706-name-167" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-167" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-167" type="surname" value="LARKIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-167" type="given" value="JOHN SMYTH"></interp>JOHN SMYTH LARKIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a hatter, and live in High-street, Shadwell. On the 30th of June, I missed a cap from the side of my shop door—I saw the prisoner the next night standing near my door—a neighbour sent a message over to me, which induced me to take him into custody—I found the cap on his head, which I had missed the night before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350706-name-168" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-168" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-168" type="surname" value="EYLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-168" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN EYLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live opposite Mr. Larkin. I saw the prisoner opposite his house—I had seen him the night before, passing the window with the cap in his hand—he seemed confused, and spoke to another lad, and ran away—I immediately went over to Mr. Larkin, to ask if he had lost a cap—he said he had, and next evening I saw the prisoner passing with the cap on his head, and went over to the prosecutor, who secured him.</p>
               <p>
